          "id": 31256,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Point B, when the aortic valve is open and the blood is being ejected into the aorta.</span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 31257,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Point C, at the peak of systolic pressure within the aorta.</span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 31258,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Point D, during the closing of the aortic valve.</span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 31259,
          "text": "<p><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Point E, in the phase of isovolumic relaxation.</span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">A 75-year-old male with a history of coronary artery disease is undergoing a routine echocardiogram that shows a normal aortic pressure waveform and the timing of coronary blood flow during the cardiac cycle. At which point on the aortic pressure waveform diagram provided is the coronary blood flow the greatest?</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/03/01/30.jpg\" style=\"height:212px; width:300px\" /></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q4606853",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 33363,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        2
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ans. D) Point E, in the phase of isovolumic relaxation.</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Option D:</strong>&nbsp; <strong>Coronary blood flow</strong> is at its <strong>greatest during early diastole (Point E),</strong> when the <strong>heart muscle is relaxed</strong> and the <strong>aortic pressure is still relatively high</strong>, which facilitates blood flow into the coronary circulation.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Explanation</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Option A.</strong> <strong>Incorrect.</strong> During <strong>systolic ejection (Point B),</strong> <strong>coronary blood flow</strong> to the <strong>myocardium is not at its peak</strong> due to the compression of the coronary arteries by the contracting heart muscle.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Option B.</strong> <strong>Incorrect</strong>. At the <strong>peak of the systolic pressure (Point C),</strong> the <strong>coronary vessels</strong> are still <strong>compressed by the contracting myocardium</strong>, which impedes blood flow to the heart muscle.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Option C.</strong> <strong>Incorrect</strong>. As the <strong>aortic valve closes (Point D),</strong> there is a brief period where <strong>coronary blood flow is not maximal</strong> due to ongoing myocardial contraction and resultant coronary vessel compression.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong><u> </u></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Understand that the <strong>greatest coronary blood flow</strong> occurs <strong>early in diastole during isovolumic relaxation</strong>, when <strong>ventricular pressure decreases</strong>, reducing <strong>compression of the coronary arteries</strong>, and the aortic pressure is still high enough to drive blood into the coronary vessels.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Refer</span></u></strong><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: Ganong&rsquo;s Review of Medical physiology, 26<sup>th</sup> edition, pg no: 599</span></strong></span></span></p>",
