      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">A 52-year-old woman with a history of dehydration, particularly during temperature fluctuations. The consulting Physician takes this opportunity to discuss how various organs regulate their blood flow, especially under different environmental conditions. Which of the following organs does not regulate its blood flow through </span></span><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">local control</span></span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">?</span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q3565432",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 33362,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        2
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ans. A) Skin</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Option A.</strong> The <strong>skin</strong> primarily <strong>regulates its blood flow through sympathetic nervous system</strong> control, mainly for <strong>thermoregulatory purposes</strong>, rather than <strong>autoregulation mechanisms</strong> that maintain <strong>constant flow</strong> despite changes in <strong>perfusion pressure</strong>.</span></span></span><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Explanation</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><strong>Option B.</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Incorrect</strong>. <strong>Muscle</strong> tissue exhibits <strong>autoregulation, particularly during exercise</strong>, where blood flow increases significantly to meet metabolic demands.</span></span></span><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><strong>Option C.</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Incorrect</strong>. <strong>Splanchnic vessels</strong>, which supply the <strong>gastrointestinal tract and other abdominal organs, also exhibit autoregulation</strong>, adjusting blood flow based on the organs&#39; metabolic needs.</span></span></span><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><strong>Option D.</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Incorrect</strong>. The <strong>cerebrum</strong> has a <strong>well-developed autoregulatory mechanism</strong> to ensure a <strong>constant blood flow</strong> despite fluctuations in systemic blood pressure, critical for maintaining neural function.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong><u> </u></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Understand that while <strong>many organs utilize autoregulation to maintain constant blood flow despite changes in blood pressure</strong>, the <strong>skin</strong> primarily uses <strong>sympathetic control for blood flow</strong> regulation, particularly for thermoregulation.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">(Refer: Ganong&rsquo;s Review of Medical physiology, 25<sup>th</sup> edition, pg no: 613)</span></strong></span></span></p>",
